Context

Serious brain related health issues like Alzheimer’s and Stroke have been a persistent crisis that organizations like yours have been striving to prevent and mitigate for many years. We have developed some treatments for these ailments, but we are still working towards better ways to discover who is most at risk. Research done by the World Health Organization in 2022 has shown that the risk of developing a stroke has increased by 50% over the last 17 years and that currently, 1 in 4 people is estimated to have a stroke in their lifetime. For Alzheimer’s, data from your website (The Alzheimer’s association) has shown that more than 6 million Americans are living with Alzheimer’s and project that by 2050, this number will rise to nearly 13 million. These are growing problems across the globe and gaining a better understanding of how to predict these diseases and what the leading causes are is vital to your work of helping millions of patients. In this paper, we are attempting to use predictive statistical modeling in order to gain insight into what specific variables are having the biggest effect on people developing these diseases, as well as provide a way to predict what patients might be at a higher risk of problems.

Introduction

Your organizations, the American Stroke Association and the Alzheimer’s Association, can greatly benefit from predictive modeling into brain related ailments. By creating and delivering a predictive model we can assist your organizations in identifying key risks of these diseases and assist doctors in making proper diagnoses and quickly begin preventative or early treatment. This project is split into two fields of brain related ailments, either the stroke or Alzheimer’s. We hope to specifically identify the unique risk factors associated with each of these diseases to further the study of brain related illness in the medical field. While these ailments are not specifically related, they impact similar parts of the body and a great body of work exists in preventing, diagnosing, and treating both of these brain ailments. Our research and model building will be delivered to your organizations in the hopes of identifying stroke and Alzheimer’s hazards. Your organizations can disperse this modeling to doctors around the country to help these individuals provide more accurate diagnostics for their patients and further educate these patients on the risks and prevention methods. 

In order to build these predictive models, we have gathered two datasets on Alzheimer’s and stroke patients. These datasets were found online and will be provided below in our preliminary investigation. Our Alzheimer’s dataset was provided by The Open Access Series of Imaging Studies (OASIS), which is “a project aimed at making MRI data sets of the brain freely available to the scientific community”. By collecting and freely releasing their MRI data, they hope to inspire future discoveries in the clinical neuroscience space. OASIS data is managed and released by the Washington University Alzheimer’s Disease Research Center, Dr. Randy Buckner at the Howard Hughes Medical Institute (HHMI)( at Harvard University, the Neuroinformatics Research Group (NRG) at Washington University School of Medicine, and the Biomedical Informatics Research Network (BIRN). Further, our Stroke dataset was provided by McKinsey Healthcare, and it is normally used as a research example dataset for classroom problems and simulation. Nevertheless, each row in our dataset represents a patient of either ailment, and key demographic and health related information for our use in predictive modeling. In addition, we have the outcome diagnosis for all patients so that we can use our models under supervised learning, to train our model for future prediction use. In the stroke dataset we will use the “stroke” variable, which is a 1 if the patient had a stroke or a 0 if the patient did not have a stroke. This is our outcome variable on whether or not the patient in the study had a stroke. Additionally,  we will use the following predictors with their values below.

1) gender: “Male”, “Female” or “Other”

2) age: age of the patient

3) hypertension: 0 if the patient doesn’t have hypertension, 1 if the patient has hypertension

4) heart_disease: 0 if the patient doesn’t have any heart diseases, 1 if the patient has a heart disease

5) ever_married: “No” or “Yes”

6) work_type: “children”, “Govt_jov”, “Never_worked”, “Private” or “Self-employed”

7) Residence_type: “Rural” or “Urban”

8) avg_glucose_level: average glucose level in blood

9) bmi: body mass index

10) smoking_status: “formerly smoked”, “never smoked”, “smokes” or “Unknown”*

In the Alzheimer’s dataset we will use the CDR variable, or Clinical Dementia Rating, which is a doctor formulated score on a scale of 0 to 5, measuring the level of dementia in a patient, with 0 being no dementia and 5 being terminal dementia. This variable will help us to create classifications of the extent to which a patient suffers from Alzheimer’s or not. 

For the Alzheimer’s data set we will use the following predictors with their values below.

Age --> Age in years

EDUC --> Years of Education

SES --> Socioeconomic Status / 1-5 where 1 is low and 5 is high

MMSE --> Mini Mental State Examination which is scored out of 30 questions, and measures cognitive impairment, with 30 being perfect and below 23 usually indicating some impairment

CDR --> Clinical Dementia Rating is a doctor formulated score on a scale of 0 to 5, measuring the level of dementia in a patient, with 0 being no dementia and 5 being terminal dementia

eTIV --> Estimated total intracranial volume is a measure of the total brain volume, where smaller volumes denote brain loss. Measured in mL.

nWBV --> Normalize Whole Brain Volume is a measure of the total head volume and is normalized on a scale between 0 and 1 where 1 is the largest brain recorded and 0 being none. 

ASF --> Atlas Scaling Factor is a factor from MRI scans measuring brain expansion or contraction. 

Most of the data is already cleaned and no variables need to be omitted. The only cleaning that needs to occur is making the numeric indicator variables factors for both datasets. Following this we will perform preliminary analyses and basic model fitting before moving on to more advanced modeling techniques for the best predictive ability.

Now we wanted to address some ethical considerations before moving on to more in depth research and analysis.  The positive outcomes with our research is that individuals at risk for stroke or Alzheimer’s will have the benefit of risk education for their potential of both diseases. Both disease associations can gain knowledge on the field and help to educate doctors and patients on the risks of stroke or Alzheimer’s. Doctors can be assisted on diagnoses with predictive modeling to accurately diagnose both issues early to start preventative care or treatment. On the other hand, there are some concerns with equity. Doctors or groups in rural or low income regions who may not have access to running the predictive modeling may not gain access to our modeling. These groups may be left without these computer assisted diagnostics and left with regular diagnostics and treatment. Hopefully equitable access can be achieved to help rural or low income areas catch up in diagnostic modeling for these two diseases. Further, every statistical model will always have some error, and lead us to wrong predictions or assessments of risk. This could lead to someone who is not at risk of a brain ailment to be worried and make drastic lifestyle changes, when drastic changes were not necessarily required. We must be careful with our validation and disbursement of these resources to ensure our work is being used for the good of the people and that we get the maximum benefit out of these models. 

Additionally, there are no names or identifiers with the dataset so we need not worry about confidentiality of our subjects. There is no way to match up the demographics with the patient. Of course, it is always best to be safe with the data so it will be smart to provide organizations with the trained model but be careful with which demographic information we are sharing.

Finally, we will give this modeling to your two organizations with education and warnings of potential downsides such as inequity of use. We will work with your associations to develop a plan to use this model equally in doctor’s offices and in risk education programs to make sure equity is kept in the model’s use. Communication and monitoring are key to ensuring the proper use of this model for healthcare.

Previous Work

  1. https://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/document?repid=rep1&type=pdf&doi=b6985d127a1c419edca437f4c71589e744699b44

This report from 2012 called “Effective Analysis and Predictive Model of Stroke Disease using Classification Methods” details the creation of a predictive model using similar methods to ones we have learned about in class, mainly decision trees and classification methods, as well as methods we haven’t discussed (naive bayes, and neural networks) in order to create a predictive model for stroke disease. Their dataset mainly uses specific symptoms and the amount of years patients have been experiencing them for, and predicts the likelihood and timing of a stroke for each patient. Our model will be unique by incorporating other variables, such as outside factors about each patient’s lives and separate symptoms that aren’t necessarily correlated with strokes. We will also examine Alzhiemer’s, which isn’t included in this article’s model.

  1. https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s12883-021-02276-8

This report from 2021 called “Construction of a risk prediction model for Alzheimer’s disease in the elderly population” uses data from 1099 elderly people obtained through clinical data and questionnaires. 9 variables were studied using LASSO, regression analysis was used to select the best predictor variables, and multivariate logistic regression analysis was used to construct the prediction model. Their variables are similar to ours (age, economic status, etc) but we have a wider variable pool and will also study the interaction between these 2 cognitive diseases which will expand on their model. We also have a wider range of ages, not focusing specifically on the elderly.

With this information and more, we can assess which types of models will best serve the purpose of our exploration and analysis, accounting for the type of data we have available.

Table 1 above displays the distribution of our response variable, Clinical Dementia Ratings, in our data. Selected Models

After exploring our data and fitting many different model types for both the Alzheimer’s and Stroke Data we find and fit our best model approaches for both. This section will show the final model fits and associated model summaries and metrics for both of our models.

Alzheimer’s

After exploring our variables we selected age, gender, MMSE, and whole brain volume for our final model fit. This was based upon an exploration of the variables along with a backwards selection method to explore our variable importance. Then, we fit our model with the following approaches: KNN, Random Forests, LDA, QDA, and SVM, all key classification methods. Based upon cross validation and hyperparameter tuning for eligible model types, we found that the LDA (Linear Discriminant Analysis) had the highest cross validated metrics for our dataset. In an LDA approach, we split the data with lines consisting of our variables to produce a score equation. Then we can calculate which side of the line an observation lands on such that we will be able to group the CDR accurately for a future observation. The metrics and fit are shown and described below.

Stroke

In the variable selection process, we explored our variable relationships and a backwards selection model to find age, hypertension, heart disease, working type, and bmi as the most important variables. Then, we began our model building by fitting our data with the following approaches: KNN, Random Forests, logistic regression, LDA, QDA, and SVM, all key classification methods. Based upon cross validation and hyperparameter tuning for eligible model types, we found that the random forest model with a tuned hyperparameter variable subset of 2 and minimum n of 21 produced the strongest prediction power. In this model approach, we create boundary decisions on our variables to separate out groups better and better, forming decision trees. We then subsample our data and variables to allow different variables to contribute more to the model, forming a forest that decides via decision vote on our classification of stroke or not. Our hyperparameters mean we choose a subset of 2 variables in each decision tree and require the minimum number of observations to be 21 in each final decision branch to prevent overfitting. The metrics and fit are shown and described below.

## Context

Serious brain related health issues like Alzheimer's and Stroke have been a persistent crisis that organizations like yours have been striving to prevent and mitigate for many years. We have developed some treatments for these ailments, but we are still working towards better ways to discover who is most at risk. Research done by the World Health Organization in 2022 has shown that the risk of developing a stroke has increased by 50% over the last 17 years and that currently, 1 in 4 people is estimated to have a stroke in their lifetime. For Alzheimer's, data from your website (The Alzheimer's association) has shown that more than 6 million Americans are living with Alzheimer's and project that by 2050, this number will rise to nearly 13 million. These are growing problems across the globe and gaining a better understanding of how to predict these diseases and what the leading causes are is vital to your work of helping millions of patients. In this paper, we are attempting to use predictive statistical modeling in order to gain insight into what specific variables are having the biggest effect on people developing these diseases, as well as provide a way to predict what patients might be at a higher risk of problems.

## Introduction

Your organizations, the American Stroke Association and the Alzheimer's Association, can greatly benefit from predictive modeling into brain related ailments. By creating and delivering a predictive model we can assist your organizations in identifying key risks of these diseases and assist doctors in making proper diagnoses and quickly begin preventative or early treatment. This project is split into two fields of brain related ailments, either the stroke or Alzheimer's. We hope to specifically identify the unique risk factors associated with each of these diseases to further the study of brain related illness in the medical field. While these ailments are not specifically related, they impact similar parts of the body and a great body of work exists in preventing, diagnosing, and treating both of these brain ailments. Our research and model building will be delivered to your organizations in the hopes of identifying stroke and Alzheimer's hazards. Your organizations can disperse this modeling to doctors around the country to help these individuals provide more accurate diagnostics for their patients and further educate these patients on the risks and prevention methods. 

In order to build these predictive models, we have gathered two datasets on Alzheimer's and stroke patients. These datasets were found online and will be provided below in our preliminary investigation. Our Alzheimer's dataset was provided by The [Open Access Series of Imaging Studies (OASIS)](http://www.oasis-brains.org/), which is "a project aimed at making MRI data sets of the brain freely available to the scientific community". By collecting and freely releasing their MRI data, they hope to inspire future discoveries in the clinical neuroscience space. OASIS data is managed and released by the Washington University Alzheimer's Disease Research Center, Dr. Randy Buckner at the [Howard Hughes Medical Institute (HHMI)](http://www.hhmi.org/)( at Harvard University, the [Neuroinformatics Research Group (NRG)](http://nrg.wustl.edu/) at Washington University School of Medicine, and the [Biomedical Informatics Research Network (BIRN)](http://www.nbirn.net/). Further, our Stroke dataset was provided by McKinsey Healthcare, and it is normally used as a research example dataset for classroom problems and simulation. Nevertheless, each row in our dataset represents a patient of either ailment, and key demographic and health related information for our use in predictive modeling. In addition, we have the outcome diagnosis for all patients so that we can use our models under supervised learning, to train our model for future prediction use. In the stroke dataset we will use the "stroke" variable, which is a 1 if the patient had a stroke or a 0 if the patient did not have a stroke. This is our outcome variable on whether or not the patient in the study had a stroke. Additionally,  we will use the following predictors with their values below.

1\) gender: "Male", "Female" or "Other"

2\) age: age of the patient

3\) hypertension: 0 if the patient doesn't have hypertension, 1 if the patient has hypertension

4\) heart_disease: 0 if the patient doesn't have any heart diseases, 1 if the patient has a heart disease

5\) ever_married: "No" or "Yes"

6\) work_type: "children", "Govt_jov", "Never_worked", "Private" or "Self-employed"

7\) Residence_type: "Rural" or "Urban"

8\) avg_glucose_level: average glucose level in blood

9\) bmi: body mass index

10\) smoking_status: "formerly smoked", "never smoked", "smokes" or "Unknown"\*

In the Alzheimer's dataset we will use the CDR variable, or Clinical Dementia Rating, which is a doctor formulated score on a scale of 0 to 5, measuring the level of dementia in a patient, with 0 being no dementia and 5 being terminal dementia. This variable will help us to create classifications of the extent to which a patient suffers from Alzheimer's or not. 

For the Alzheimer's data set we will use the following predictors with their values below.

Age \--\> Age in years

EDUC \--\> Years of Education

SES \--\> Socioeconomic Status / 1-5 where 1 is low and 5 is high

MMSE \--\> Mini Mental State Examination which is scored out of 30 questions, and measures cognitive impairment, with 30 being perfect and below 23 usually indicating some impairment

CDR \--\> Clinical Dementia Rating is a doctor formulated score on a scale of 0 to 5, measuring the level of dementia in a patient, with 0 being no dementia and 5 being terminal dementia

eTIV \--\> Estimated total intracranial volume is a measure of the total brain volume, where smaller volumes denote brain loss. Measured in mL.

nWBV \--\> Normalize Whole Brain Volume is a measure of the total head volume and is normalized on a scale between 0 and 1 where 1 is the largest brain recorded and 0 being none. 

ASF \--\> Atlas Scaling Factor is a factor from MRI scans measuring brain expansion or contraction. 

Most of the data is already cleaned and no variables need to be omitted. The only cleaning that needs to occur is making the numeric indicator variables factors for both datasets. Following this we will perform preliminary analyses and basic model fitting before moving on to more advanced modeling techniques for the best predictive ability.

Now we wanted to address some ethical considerations before moving on to more in depth research and analysis.  The positive outcomes with our research is that individuals at risk for stroke or Alzheimer's will have the benefit of risk education for their potential of both diseases. Both disease associations can gain knowledge on the field and help to educate doctors and patients on the risks of stroke or Alzheimer's. Doctors can be assisted on diagnoses with predictive modeling to accurately diagnose both issues early to start preventative care or treatment. On the other hand, there are some concerns with equity. Doctors or groups in rural or low income regions who may not have access to running the predictive modeling may not gain access to our modeling. These groups may be left without these computer assisted diagnostics and left with regular diagnostics and treatment. Hopefully equitable access can be achieved to help rural or low income areas catch up in diagnostic modeling for these two diseases. Further, every statistical model will always have some error, and lead us to wrong predictions or assessments of risk. This could lead to someone who is not at risk of a brain ailment to be worried and make drastic lifestyle changes, when drastic changes were not necessarily required. We must be careful with our validation and disbursement of these resources to ensure our work is being used for the good of the people and that we get the maximum benefit out of these models. 

Additionally, there are no names or identifiers with the dataset so we need not worry about confidentiality of our subjects. There is no way to match up the demographics with the patient. Of course, it is always best to be safe with the data so it will be smart to provide organizations with the trained model but be careful with which demographic information we are sharing.

Finally, we will give this modeling to your two organizations with education and warnings of potential downsides such as inequity of use. We will work with your associations to develop a plan to use this model equally in doctor's offices and in risk education programs to make sure equity is kept in the model's use. Communication and monitoring are key to ensuring the proper use of this model for healthcare.

This report from 2012 called "Effective Analysis and Predictive Model of Stroke Disease using Classification Methods" details the creation of a predictive model using similar methods to ones we have learned about in class, mainly decision trees and classification methods, as well as methods we haven't discussed (naive bayes, and neural networks) in order to create a predictive model for stroke disease. Their dataset mainly uses specific symptoms and the amount of years patients have been experiencing them for, and predicts the likelihood and timing of a stroke for each patient. Our model will be unique by incorporating other variables, such as outside factors about each patient's lives and separate symptoms that aren't necessarily correlated with strokes. This report from 2021 called "Construction of a risk prediction model for Alzheimer's disease in the elderly population" uses data from 1099 elderly people obtained through clinical data and questionnaires. 9 variables were studied using LASSO, regression analysis was used to select the best predictor variables, and multivariate logistic regression analysis was used to construct the prediction model. Their variables are similar to ours (age, economic status, etc) but we have a wider variable pool and will also study the interaction between these 2 cognitive diseases which will expand on their model. We also have a wider range of ages, not focusing specifically on the elderly.

## Selected Models

After exploring our data and fitting many different model types for both the Alzheimer's and Stroke Data we find and fit our best model approaches for both. This section will show the final model fits and associated model summaries and metrics for both of our models.

### Alzheimer's

After exploring our variables we selected age, gender, MMSE, and whole brain volume for our final model fit. This was based upon an exploration of the variables along with a backwards selection method to explore our variable importance. Then, we fit our model with the following approaches: KNN, Random Forests, LDA, QDA, and SVM, all key classification methods. Based upon cross validation and hyperparameter tuning for eligible model types, we found that the LDA (Linear Discriminant Analysis) had the highest cross validated metrics for our dataset. In an LDA approach, we split the data with lines consisting of our variables to produce a score equation. Then we can calculate which side of the line an observation lands on such that we will be able to group the CDR accurately for a future observation. The metrics and fit are shown and described below.

#### Metrics

```{r}
alz_metrics <- workflow_lda_alz %>%
  fit_resamples(alz_cvs,
                metrics = metric_set(recall, precision, specificity, accuracy, roc_auc)) %>%
  collect_metrics()
```

```{r}
alz_metrics
```

Our model had the above cross validated metrics, the key metrics being accuracy at 0.722 and ROC at 0.828. While these metrics are not as strong as we would like them to be for very strong future prediction, we can accurately diagnose Alzheimer's with 72% accuracy. This model could be key in assisting doctor diagnoses and recommendations in the office, as well as serve as a stepping stone for future model building and improvements.

#### Fit

```{r}
fit_alz <- workflow_lda_alz %>%
  fit(alz)
fit_alz %>% pull_workflow_fit()
```

```{r}
alz %>%
  mutate(
    preds = predict(fit_alz, alz)$.pred_class
  ) %>%
  conf_mat(truth = CDR,
           estimate = preds)
```

Here we can see the fitted linear discriminant analysis with our three discriminant lines separating our CDR ratings along with our sample data confusion matrix. Our fitted model shows that all four variables are key players in building our discriminating lines, and when we fit the original dataset with out model we have fairly strong prediction accuracy, with the largest issue being the model predicting too many cases of Alzheimer's as a 0 clinical dementia rating. Of course, this is on our training data and we should always refer to the above cross validated metrics for our model and estimating the future performance in the field.

### Stroke

In the variable selection process, we explored our variable relationships and a backwards selection model to find age, hypertension, heart disease, working type, and bmi as the most important variables. Then, we began our model building by fitting our data with the following approaches: KNN, Random Forests, logistic regression, LDA, QDA, and SVM, all key classification methods. Based upon cross validation and hyperparameter tuning for eligible model types, we found that the random forest model with a tuned hyperparameter variable subset of 2 and minimum n of 21 produced the strongest prediction power. In this model approach, we create boundary decisions on our variables to separate out groups better and better, forming decision trees. We then subsample our data and variables to allow different variables to contribute more to the model, forming a forest that decides via decision vote on our classification of stroke or not. Our hyperparameters mean we choose a subset of 2 variables in each decision tree and require the minimum number of observations to be 21 in each final decision branch to prevent overfitting. The metrics and fit are shown and described below.

#### Metrics

Tuned in Code Above

This is not the strongest accuracy we could hope for, but it certainly will help to provide support and assistance to doctors already providing diagnostics.

## Conclusion

After exploring and analyzing our Alzheimer's and stroke data, we have prepared two final models for use by your organizations. For the Alzheimer's Association we have prepared our best possible model using a linear discriminant analysis approach. Using cross validation we can estimate that our model will accurately diagnose patients 72% of the time. While this is low for diagnosing such a serious ailment, where we want to minimize the number of missed cases and number of false positives, our current model can help in three key areas. First, the model can be deployed with doctors and current diagnostics, to assist in providing diagnoses and providing a preliminary estimate of the patients outcome. This model used in conjunction with preexisting diagnostics and understanding of the disease can only help to improve a doctor's diagnosis. The second area will include education for doctors and the Alzheimer's association. Analyzing the prediction patterns of this model can help to expand our understanding of the underlying causes of the disease, and hopefully identify some steps to prevent the disease. Lastly, this model serves as a key starting point for future model building. As more patients and more variables are found, along with more understanding of the disease we can update the training of our model to hopefully one day reach an optimal prediction level for Alzheimer's. While the model may not be up to par today, it serves as a key stepping stone for future analysis and model building in the Alzheimer's diagnostic field.

For the American Stroke Association, we have prepared a random forest model with a similar cross validated accuracy of 0.72. This means we can accurately diagnose a patient 72% of the time in the future. As with our message to the Alzheimer's assocaition above, this model could still use some improvement for such a serious disease. This model still provides the same benefits above that will benefit your organization. Use of the model in conjunction with doctors and existing measures will only serve to help the diagnoses of future patients. Further experimentation of the model can help to educate doctors and researchers on the causes of stroke and how we might prevent it. This model is also a great starting point for future training and modeling as researchers understand more about the disease and we gather more variables and patients to analyze.

While both final models leave something to desire, they provide important benefits for both the Alzheimer's Association and the American Stroke Association.

## Reflection

Our main goal was to provide quality models and analysis to both the Alzheimer's Association and the American Stroke Association. The challenges we faced mainly consisted of data cleaning and organization along with low model metrics. We gained valuable experience in locating, researching, and preparing data for analysis which we did not do much in regular class assignments. Then we got to see how a model building analysis would go in a real world assignment where we are catering to a clients needs and doing a project for the good of the world, not just for fun. Overall, the project was a valuable experience and bolstered the skills we acquired in this course.
